defaultAppendix A:defaultWhy the Part L decision is flaweddefaultFirstly, at 
defaultconsultation stage the cost of the ‘halfway point’ policy was stated to be £453 million (i.e. it would cost house builders that amount to comply with it). This figure was based on out-of-date figures, for example the costs for installing solar PV have fall
defaulten by approximately 45% since this time. The real cost to house builders would in fact be £317 million. In the published changes DECC acknowledges the latest solar PV costs in the new non-domestic buildings analysis and yet the less ambitious target was st
defaultill preferred.
defaultSecondly, the benefits to private consumers were ignored. The Impact Assessment for options for the 2013 building regulations openly failed to take into account the benefits to consumers of the policy, contrary to the rules in the Treasury ‘
defaultgreen book’, which specifies that all costs and benefits
default defaultshould be assessed. This meant that benefits to consumers of fuel savings of £375 million were ignored.
defaultIf the
defaultse 
defaultfigures are used instead
default, 
defaultthey show that the halfway approach would benefit society by
default £58m (£375m benefit - £317m costs)
